{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 16:21:34.404562", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Submission completed.\n\nSummary of submission:\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: [\"server_access_router\"]\n- root_cause_name: [\"ospf_area_misconfiguration\"]\n\nNotes:\n- The diagnostic report identified that the server backend network (10.200.0.0/24) is directly connected on the server_access_router and is being advertised into OSPF, allowing user hosts to reach backend servers directly. This is a policy/segmentation design violation. The server_access_router and its OSPF advertisement of the backend subnet are the locus of the problem; I categorized the root cause as \"ospf_area_misconfiguration\" because the unintended advertisement/visibility of the backend subnet into the OSPF domain is the configuration issue enabling the fault.\n\nIf you want, I can now prepare suggested remediation steps (specific FRR config changes, ACLs, or routing policy options) to enforce that only the load‑balancer is reachable from user subnets and backends are isolated.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 2426, "output_tokens": 205, "total_tokens": 2631, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 1664}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
